12
00:00:44,570 --> 00:00:45,200
Analyzing.

13
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:47,750
The main primary domain model is order.

14
00:00:47,750 --> 00:00:54,170
An order is an aggregate root with the properties such as the customer ID, order name, shipping address,

15
00:00:54,170 --> 00:00:58,280
billing address, payment status, and the list of the order items.

16
00:00:58,280 --> 00:01:01,400
So the next domain entity is order item.

17
00:01:01,400 --> 00:01:07,880
Order item is an entity associated with the order and containing fields like the product ID, quantity

18
00:01:07,880 --> 00:01:08,780
and price.

19
00:01:08,780 --> 00:01:13,430
So the order and order item entities has one to many relationships.

20
00:01:13,910 --> 00:01:17,210
You can also see the class including the order aggregate.

21
00:01:17,210 --> 00:01:23,060
See that order entity is inherited from the aggregate and including the order items, customer ID,

22
00:01:23,060 --> 00:01:26,030
order name, shipping address, billing address and so on.

23
00:01:26,610 --> 00:01:31,800
So also we can consider integration events for order created action.

24
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:37,320
Here you can see that we can throw an order created event from the order domain model.

25
00:01:37,590 --> 00:01:42,810
The next step is application use case analyzing for ordering microservices.

26
